metadata.name: Floatrest #153
metadata.description:
Floating forests over the endless sky, where birds, trees, plants, roots, rocks and waterfalls share an ecosystem full of life and emotion.

You can see some rain clouds in the sky and the sun shining under the raindrops.

The earth is moving, the blocks are falling, but the trees are strong in their roots.

Welcome to 'Floatrest'.

----

# Features

- 7 tree palettes
- 17 different background colors
- 10 different terrain colors
- clouds
- vines
- roots
- plants
- waterfall
- birds
- sun / moon
- night
- dark mode
- monochromatic
- 2 different aspect ratios (square & portrait)
- Press "p" on live mode to save in PNG

This artwork requires processing power and is intended for laptops and desktops primarily. It may take some time to render.

----

July 2022, gpitombo

metadata.name: Plottable Field (8 frames) #10
metadata.description:
'Field' explores the realm of noise field distortions through many different primitives: 15 unique distributions, 16 possible inks, and many kinds of distortions, ink combinations, and animations,...

A SVG file can be exported (right-click save) to plot the 8 frames of this animation on a A4 paper. This is a "plot loop". The physical piece is displayed as aesthetics 4x2 grid of the frames.

You can enjoy the digital version that simulates ink effects. But also, thanks to the utility token decoupling, get a physical one: the digital NFT is the recipe to a plottable art piece, owning it confers the right to plot or request a physical plot from @greweb (https://greweb.me/plots/nft). @greweb would use fountain pens but other plotting artists are free to achieve it with their materials and ship to collectors – as long as NFT is owned at request time.

metadata.name: Miniscapes #231
metadata.description:
Miniscapes merges generative code (Rich's bit) with meticulously designed scenes and elements (Rick's bit), to create minimalist landscapes intended to charm, delight, and surprise.

Our aim was to convey as much as possible with as little as possible by using simple shapes and lines to represent a wide variety of natural landscapes.

We hope that you find as much joy in owning a Miniscape as we did in creating them.

Controls (in live view):
- Press [s] to save the current image
- Press [p] to pause an animated output
- Press [r] to reset an animated output (this will also pause)

metadata.name: fabrics #102
metadata.description:
'fabrics' explores textile art made with code mixing different patterns of very small lines.

Inspiration from Anni Albers works, Antoni Tàpies and Studio Yorktown for the patterns and the colours. Also oriental rugs and clothes from around the world had been used for the palettes.
Palettes: Monochrome, Kilt, Kilim, Austral, Peruvian, Afghan, Berber, Nain, Fur, Jeans, Kente, Bogolan, Albers, Sabler.

Press [s] to save an 1200x1360 image (.png).
Click on it to change the orientation of the stitches.

Generative art made using p5js. By @mehno_art

metadata.description:
Nothing is true to reality about this piece.
Not the sky, nor the hills and definitely not the colors. 
It’s all about getting lost in a place we don’t know - A puzzle, a mystery and collecting the missing pieces.

Press “s” to save as png.

Made with p5js;
